  "local_port": 55828,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Being an engineer (not a student) how can i get an internship (preferably research) from iisc or iit?",
  "response": "To secure a research internship at IISc or IIT as a working professional, follow this structured approach:\n\n### 1. **Target Identification**\n   - **Research Alignment**: Identify departments and faculty at IISc/IITs whose research aligns with your expertise or interests. Use institutional websites, recent publications, and projects to shortlist professors.\n   - **Industry Collaboration Programs**: Explore formal industry-academia partnerships (e.g., IISc\u2019s Society for Innovation and Development or IITs\u2019 Corporate Relations Centers) that might facilitate internships.\n\n### 2. **Proactive Outreach**\n   - **Tailored Communication**: Draft a concise email to professors, highlighting:\n     - Your industry experience and how it complements their research.\n     - Specific ideas or projects you\u2019d like to contribute to (reference their recent work).\n     - Flexibility in terms of part-time, remote, or short-term engagement.\n   - **Attach Documents**: Include a CV, project portfolio, and a brief proposal if applicable.\n\n### 3. **Leverage Networks**\n   - **Conferences/Seminars**: Attend virtual or in-person events hosted by these institutions to network with faculty.\n   - **Professional Platforms**: Use LinkedIn to connect with researchers or join academic groups for updates on opportunities.\n\n### 4. **Formal Programs**\n   - **Visiting Fellowships**: Check for programs like IISc\u2019s Visiting Scientist or IITs\u2019 Visiting Scholar positions, which cater to professionals.\n   - **Sponsored Projects**: Propose a collaboration funded by your employer or through grants (e.g., DST, CSIR schemes).\n\n### 5. **Logistical Considerations**\n   - **Flexibility**: Offer to work remotely or on a flexible schedule. Consider a sabbatical if full-time commitment is needed.\n   - **Employer Support**: Discuss IP/legal terms with your employer; seek sponsorship or leave if possible.\n\n### 6. **Persistence and Follow-Up**\n   - Politely follow up if there\u2019s no initial response. Highlight mutual benefits (e.g., bridging industry and academia).\n\n### Example Email Outline:\n```plaintext\nSubject: Interest in Collaborative Research Opportunity\n\nDear Prof. [Name],\n\nI am [Your Name], a [Your Job Title] at [Company], with expertise in [Area]. I admire your work on [Specific Project/Paper] and believe my industry experience in [Skill/Project] could contribute to your research on [Topic].\n\nI am keen to explore a short-term internship or collaboration, potentially focusing on [Idea]. I am flexible with timing and open to remote/part-time engagement.\n\nAttached are my CV and portfolio for your review. I would welcome the chance to discuss this further.\n\nThank you for your consideration.\n\nBest regards,\n[Your Name]\n```\n\n### Key Resources:\n- **IISc Research Divisions**: [https://www.iisc.ac.in/](https://www.iisc.ac.in/)\n- **IIT Collaboration Portals**: Check individual IIT websites (e.g., IIT Bombay\u2019s IRCC).\n- **Funding Schemes**: Explore DST\u2019s Industry-Academia Collaborative Projects.\n\nBy strategically aligning your industry expertise with academic goals and demonstrating initiative, you can increase your chances of securing a research internship. Persistence and clarity on mutual benefits are key!",
